For art collectors, there are few movies that better capture the
romance of the auction house than The Red Violin, in which Samuel L. Jackso=
n plays an appraiser summoned to assess an instrument suspected to be the f=
amed =E2=80=9CRed Violin=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94the final violin made by the fict=
ional Italian luthier Nicol=C3=B2 Bussotti. The movie follows the instrumen=
t through the centuries, from its maker=E2=80=99s workshop in 17th century =
Cremona, Italy, to its subsequent owners in Austria, England, and China, be=
fore ending up in Canada for sale. It=E2=80=99s a beloved,
and underappreciated, classic.

=C2=A0

Life will imitate art next Friday, when Sotheby=E2=80=99s auctions the Joac=
him-Ma Stradivarius, estimated to fetch at least $12 million. (At the momen=
t, the lot does not have a guarantee or an irrevocable bid.) The instrument=
 is named for its two most well-known former owners: Joseph Joachim and Si-=
