m_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )

It=E2=80=99s become common for symphony patrons to purchase a
Stradivarius for use by a particular virtuoso, while reliably expecting to =
see a return on their investment anywhere between 4.9 percent and 7.7 perce=
nt, according ( https://www.thetimes.com/life-style/luxury/article/the-powe=
r-of-stradivarius-violins-times-luxury-8tftzjvxd?utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+=
-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F31%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281=
%2F31%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=
=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) to The Times of London. The Joachim-Ma, for instanc=
e, is considered a playing violin, as opposed to a collector=E2=80=99s piec=
e, such as Stradivari=E2=80=99s Messiah violin
at the Ashmolean Museum in Oxford. Despite signs of wear over the centuries=
, according to the condition report, =E2=80=9Cthe overall condition of the =
structure is in very good, restored condition, and in appropriate condition=
 for normal and regular playing.=E2=80=9D Jim=C3=A9nez told me that some cl=
ients who viewed the Joachim-Ma during its tour stops in London and Hong Ko=
ng were accompanied by master violinists who were allowed to play it.

=C2=A0

Will
the Joachim-Ma violin create auction magic? It has the ingredients: provena=
nce, rarity, beauty, and celebrity of the 19th century variety. As Jim=C3=
=A9nez told me, it=E2=80=99s like =E2=80=9Cseeing history, the traces of th=
e violinists who have played it.=E2=80=9D Perhaps she was laying it on, but=
 she also said that virtuosos who have had the opportunity to play the Joac=
him-Ma violin in Sotheby=E2=80=99s galleries have been brought to tears. =
=E2=80=9CThey play it and put it down,=E2=80=9D she said, =E2=80=9Cthen run=
 back to play it again.=E2=80=9D

=E2=80=8A

