=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">For art collectors, there are few movies t=
hat better capture the
romance of the auction house than <em>The Red Violin</em>, in which <strong=
>Samuel L. Jackson</strong> plays an appraiser summoned to assess an instru=
ment suspected to be the famed =E2=80=9CRed Violin=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94the fin=
al violin made by the fictional Italian <em>luthier</em> Nicol=C3=B2 Bussot=
ti. The movie follows the instrument through the centuries, from its maker=
=E2=80=99s workshop in 17th century Cremona, Italy, to its subsequent owner=
s in Austria, England, and China, before ending up in Canada for sale. It=
=E2=80=99s a beloved,
and underappreciated, classic.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=
=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">Life will imitate art next Friday, when So=
theby=E2=80=99s auctions the Joachim-Ma Stradivarius, estimated to fetch at=
 least $12 million. (At the moment, the lot does not have a guarantee or an=
 irrevocable bid.) The instrument is named for its two most well-known form=
er owners: <strong>Joseph Joachim</strong> and <strong>Si-Hon Ma</strong>. =
Joachim, who purchased the violin in 1849, was one of the
greatest violinists of his time. It=E2=80=99s believed that Joachim premier=
ed <strong>Johannes Brahms</strong>=E2=80=99s <em>Violin Concerto in D majo=
r, Op. 77</em>, on this very instrument in 1879. The catalog note features =
an 1868 photo of him holding it.</p></div>
